observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to:
Maintain the SLC based on the results of the physical count and update them regularly to reflect subsequent movements;
Implement a defined timeline for the submission of SSMIs (whether weekly, bi-weekly, or monthly) by the designated supply officers, and monitor compliance to ensure accountability and timeliness;
Record inventory purchases immediately upon delivery based on the AIR and other supporting documents, such as delivery receipts and charge invoices. Likewise, inventory issuances should be recorded based on the SSMIs submitted by the designated unit supply officers duly reviewed by the GSO-Designate. The SLCs shall be updated accordingly for both purchases and issuances;
Ensure that the AIR, copy of the delivery receipt, and copy of the charge invoice are attached to the JEV covering recorded deliveries, and that the SSMI and consolidated RIS are attached to the JEV covering recorded issuances; and
Coordinate with the distributing office regarding the recorded year-end issuances of welfare goods, retrieve copies of the corresponding RDS, and furnish these along with the related JEVs and SSMIs to this Office. Henceforth, all JEVs covering issuances of welfare goods should be supported by the corresponding RDS.
Require the Unit Supply Officers to prepare the SSMIs covering the recorded year-end issuances based on the consolidated RIS, or if unavailable, based on the stock cards maintained at the office level, and submit copies of the SSMIs to the Accounting Office for recording and submission to the Office of the Auditor. Henceforth, the Unit supply Officers shall periodically prepare SSMI based on RIS to be submitted to the GSO-Designate for review and consolidation; and
Direct the GSO -Designate to review the SSMI and RIS submitted by the Unit Supply Officers prior to submission to the Accounting Office for proper recording.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the appropriate journal entries relative to the unrecorded liabilities amounting to ₱0.298 million. Accordingly, working paper adjustment entries shall be prepared for the restatement of the affected accounts to present the correct CY 2024 restated figures in the preparation of the CY 2025 comparative FS;
Ensure that goods and services that have been delivered or rendered as at year end be properly recorded as liabilities. Relative to this, require, as year-end cut-off procedures, the Municipal General Services Office to forward to the Municipal Accounting Office all claims for delivered goods and services for the proper recognition of AP on the related transactions;
Expedite the reconciliation of the ₱0.611 million unreconciled balance of the reported AP and revert the amounts to the unappropriated surplus, as warranted; and
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly disclose in the NFS the contingent liability arising from the undelivered POs at year-end to ensure the fair presentation of the FS.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct a comprehensive review of the existing balances of the accounts “Due to NGAs” and “Due to LGUs,” and reconstruct a detailed monitoring report and/or subsidiary ledgers, disaggregated by specific agency, transaction, and fund source, to ensure traceability, accuracy, and completeness of recorded liabilities; and;
Establish and implement a regular monitoring and reconciliation process between the GL and subsidiary ledgers to validate the existence, accuracy, and aging of outstanding payables, and to promptly identify and resolve any discrepancies.

We recommended that Management:
ensure the conduct of semi-annual physical count of inventories and reconciliation of accounting and supply records. Relative to this, the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) shall be submitted to the Office of the Auditor not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO-Designate to investigate the inventory accounts with balances which remain unchanged since 2019 totaling P1,033,321.00 and prepare duly supported adjusting entries, as warranted to reflect the correct balances of the accounts.

We recommended that Management:
prioritize the strict implementation and enforcement of the documentary and procedural requirements of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 for the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances;
require the Inventory Committee and Municipal Accountant to identify the PPE items that failed to meet the P15,000.00 capitalization threshold and the latter shall prepare appropriate adjusting entries based on verifiable evidence;
direct the Municipal Accountant to investigate the negative balances of PPE items included in the supporting schedules and prepare adjusting entries as necessary; and
henceforth, require the Inventory Committee to conduct the annual physical count and prepare a report thereon to be submitted on or before January 31 of the ensuing year.

We recommended that Management:
include as a priority project the establishment of a room/building which shall serve as the storage facility for procured property and inventories prior to the release to end-user units. Relative to this, Management shall endeavor to maintain a centralized inventory management system;
pending the establishment of a storage room/warehouse, the Municipal Mayor shall designate employees, who shall be properly bonded, to manage the issuance, recording and reporting of inventories in their respective offices;
require the Agency’s Inventory Committee together with the representatives from the end-user units and the Designated GSO to conduct an inventory count on all office supplies and construction materials that are yet to be consumed as of a cut-off date to be determined by the Committee and prepare a Report on Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) for recording and control purposes;
based on the RPCI prepared, the Municipal Accountant shall prepare an entry to recognize the cost of Inventories at hand and henceforth observe the proper accounting policies and entries in the recording of transactions;
direct the Municipal Accountant and Designated GSO to maintain a record of all construction materials on a per project basis, to be regularly reconciled with the records of the Engineering Office. A report on the balance thereon shall be prepared upon the issuance by the Engineering Office of the Certificate of Completion for each successfully completed project; and
ensure that all properties of the government are properly safeguarded against deterioration, loss and wastage.

We recommended that Management:
submit explanation/justification with verifiable basis why disbursements on procurements which were noted as non-compliant with existing procurement law, as mentioned above, should not be suspended/disallowed in post-audit;
henceforth, require the BAC to submit the proof of validation on the technical, legal and financial capability of the suppliers together with Mayor’s Permit and proof of PhilGEPS Registration on all purchases made through Alternative Mode of Procurement to support eligibility of suppliers;
direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that posting requirements of RFQ, Notice of Award, Purchase Order/Contract and Notice to Proceed if necessary, on all procurement through shopping with ABC higher than P50,000.00 are complied with and proof thereof are attached to the disbursement voucher to establish correctness of information and reliability of bidding process;
direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements for the procurement of goods and services are included in the end-user PPMP and Agency APP by requiring a certification to that effect from the Head of the BAC Secretariat, who shall, based on the submissions of the end-user units, validate such fact; and
require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all essential information are provided in the supporting documents to establish the validity and legality of the transactions.

We recommended the following: 

The ICO-MSWDO to submit original copy of distribution sheet for year 2017 charged against the LDRRMF and to prepare distribution sheets for all the succeeding distribution of relief goods by batches and submit an original copy of it to COA;
The ICO-Municipal Accountant to submit also other supporting documents stated-above for the procurement of the relief goods to avoid possible suspension of the transaction;
The LDRRMA to endorse relief goods to the ICO-MSWDO by accomplishing the “Received by” portion of the RIS to account for the release and transfer of goods to be distributed to intended beneficiaries to be able to confirm the receipt of goods whenever deem necessary; and take into consideration the preparation of the budget for LDRRMF in terms of the allocation of budget for LDRRMF to render timely audit and results thereof of the Fund.

